						<summary>

						<p>On the <hi rend="italic">gōpura</hi> of the Nīlakaṇṭhēśvara temple.</p>						

						<p>This Sanskrit inscription engraved in <hi rend="italic">Grantha</hi> characters of about the 14th century consists of two verses in the <hi rend="italic">Śārdūlavikrīḍita</hi> metre.</p>						

						<p>The first verse is in praise of the deity Nīlakaṇṭha at Vishapura, worshipped by the large Nīlagrīva (<hi rend="italic">i.e.,</hi> Kaṟaikaṇṭhīśvaram-uḍaiya-nāyaṉār of Veḍāl), while the second verse speaks of seven hills in that place, named after seven persons <hi rend="italic">viz.,</hi> Phaṇīpati (i.e., Ādiśēsha), etc., who are stated to have worshipped the Īśvara here.</p>						

						</summary>
